abstract: >-
  ThermoFooty pre-registers and executes a natural-experiment test of
  the heat-aggression hypothesis on European soccer.  The design
  exploits the fact that fixtures are scheduled before weather is
  realised, eliminating the Field-1992 outdoor-opportunity confound
  that limits modern crime-data designs.  Primary confirmatory test
  (H1): time-stratified case-crossover conditional logit on Big-5
  European league matches 1970-2026, asking whether the odds that a
  referee issues a direct red card for violent conduct rise with the
  day-of-match maximum-temperature anomaly at the stadium.  Auxiliary
  battery covers crowd-violence (H2 on pooled English UK Home Office
  + German ZIS-Jahresberichte arrests), indoor-stadia attenuation,
  heat-by-stakes interactions, within-player fixed effects,
  population- and per-player breakpoint analyses, player-mobility
  natural experiments, cross-league heterogeneity, and a tournament
  panel with cooled-vs-open-stadia contrasts including Qatar 2022
  Stadium 974 as a within-tournament natural control.  Built on top
  of the ThermoStrife weather cascade (Geurten 2026, DOI
  10.5281/zenodo.20371612) and the reRandomStats statistics toolkit
  (Geurten 2026, DOI 10.5281/zenodo.20387255).
